{"cursor":"3984","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"{{Infobox Christian leader\n| name = William Ayermin title = Bishop of Norwich diocese = Diocese of Norwich\n| elected = 19 July 1325 ended = 27 March 1336 (death) predecessor = Robert\n| Baldock successor = Thomas Hemenhale\n\n| consecration = 6 February 1327\n\n| death_date = religion = Roman Catholic\n}}\n\n'William Ayermin' (or 'Ayermine' ) was a medieval Bishop\nof Norwich.\n\nAyermin's family was based in Osgodby, Lincolnshire. Two\nof his brothers achieved ecclesiastical offices as well; Adam de Ayermin became\narchdeacon of Norfolk and Richard de Ayreminne became chancellor of the dioceses\nof Norwich and Salisbury.\n\nAyermin sat in the Edward II's Parliament at Carlisle for St. Augustine's Abbey,\nCanterbury in 1306-7. He also recorded the proceedings of\nEdward II's parliament at Lincoln in 1316.\n\nAyermin was captured at the Battle of Myton (1319) with an English army\nresisting a Scottish raid during the First War of Scottish Independence. He was held prisoner by the Scots for several months.\n\nAyermin was a canon of St. Paul's, Lincoln and Hereford when he was named\nLord Privy Seal about 26 May 1324. He held that office until January or\nFebruary 1325. Fryde, et al. Handbook of British\nChronology p. 93\n\nAyermin was nominated to the see of Norwich on 19 July 1325 and was consecrated\non 6 February 1327. Fryde, et al. Handbook of British\nChronology p. 262\n\nAyermin was acting Keeper of the Great Seal, usually known as the Lord\nChancellor of England, from 1326 to 1327. Fryde, et al.\nHandbook of British Chronology p. 86\n\nAyermin held the office of Lord High Treasurer from 1331 to 1332. Fryde, et al. Handbook of British Chronology p. 101\n\nAyermin died on 27 March 1336.\n","linknr":231,"url":"William_Ayermin","recorded":1375075940,"links":["/w/index.php?title=William_Ayermin&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=William_Ayermin&action=edit","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ic